Here is an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP. We'll be using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for this example.

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>

<div class="search-container">
    <input type="text" id="search-input" placeholder="Search...">
    <button id="search-button">Search</button>
    <div id="results"></div>
</div>

<script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

**style.css**
```css
.search-container {
    width: 80%;
    margin: auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
}

#search-input {
    width: 70%;
    height: 40px;
    padding: 10px;
    font-size: 18px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px 0 0 5px;
}

#search-button {
    width: 20%;
    height: 40px;
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px;
    font-size: 18px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 0 5px 5px 0;
}

#results {
    margin-top: 20px;
}
```

**script.js**
```javascript
document.getElementById("search-button").addEventListener("click", function() {
    var searchInput = document.getElementById("search-input").value.trim();

    if (searchInput !== "") {
        fetch("search.php?q=" + searchInput)
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                var resultsHTML = "";

                data.forEach(item => {
                    resultsHTML += `
                        <div>
                            <h2>${item.title}</h2>
                            <p>${item.description}</p>
                        </div>
                    `;
                });

                document.getElementById("results").innerHTML = resultsHTML;
            })
            .catch(error => console.error(error));
    }
});
```

**search.php**
```php
<?php

// Replace this with your database connection code
$mysqli = new mysqli("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

if (isset($_GET["q"])) {
    $query = "SELECT * FROM table WHERE column LIKE '%" . $_GET["q"] . "%'";

    if ($result = $mysqli->query($query)) {
        while ($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) {
            $data[] = array(
                "title" => $row["column"],
                "description" => $row["another_column"]
            );
        }

        echo json_encode($data);
    } else {
        echo json_encode(array("error" => "No results found"));
    }

    $mysqli->close();
} else {
    http_response_code(404);
}

?>
```
This is a very basic example. You should replace `search.php` with your own database connection code and query to retrieve the search results.

The JavaScript code sends an AJAX request to `search.php` with the search input as a parameter, and displays the search results in the `#results` div.

